An interesting RISK style game. Good points: 1. Design & Graphics 2. Animation 3. Features like researching technologies and super weapons Bad points (and sorry to day these are deal breakers): There seem to be many bugs in the game 1. Sometimes when the last enemy is defeated the game freezes. And even if you restart, you can't finish as you are the only one left. At most you can destroy your own territories by attacking nearby ones (as sometimes the targeting is not accurate, but that could be intentionally done by the developers) 2. I faced two occasions where at the end of the game it showed a progress in percentage and the very next screen in main menu the percentage was reduced. I wonder if this can lead to negative percentage progress :D. 3. The Pact feature does not make sense, I mean allies can attack each other (OK maybe acceptable if someone is sneaky) but shouldn't the pact break in that case. 4. Due to the progress percentage glitch you could lose on the unlockable objects. 5. Few of the unlockable objects freeze in the middle of the game. Bottom line, I played the game and I liked it. Given the bugs noticed I would not recommend to buy it (I think there is free version available with Ads). Also, unless I see updates in this game I would not spend on any other game from the developers of this one.

I have been an RTS fan for many years, and have longed for a game like this on mobile ever since I got my hands on a mobile device. One cannot express in words the sheer joy of building a massive nuclear arsenal, then sending your least favorite national entities (for me, those were China, North Korea, and Iran) back to the stone age. I find this game is extremely fun, especially against six or more opponents; it is especially rewarding having won a game of that said scale as a small nation such as Israel. This game has depth, but not so much so as to not bog you down in details during your evening commute - a very good attribute for a mobile strategy game. Finally, this game can be both a quick skirmish, or a long, all-out war - as long as you so choose; just keep in mind that there is no save feature (which stands to reason, most games are under ten minutes anyway). Be you on a lunch break, or on your way to a peace negotiation, this game is sure to help you pass the time.

Fun game that's worth $3.  Not a lot of strategy required.  You can win building only cruise missiles if you are patient and wait while the other countries destroy each other.  Here are a couple bugs I've encountered:  1)  Sometimes my defensive missiles will shoot at ICBMs aimed at enemy countries instead of the ones aimed at me, even after I've researched the upgrade to know where all missiles are going.  Maddening to have 3 of the big super missiles coming at me and see my defensive missile save an enemy.  2)  Sometimes I'll start with a country that I can't click on.  It just sits there the entire game unable to be accessed.    3)  Other times a country will become unusable during the game.  It will show that I control it and have missiles there, but I can't access it.  4)  Maybe not a bug, but the AI doesn't seem very smart.  The advantage of the stealth bomber is supposed to be that its hard to shoot down.  But I've NEVER had the AI even try to shoot down my super missile so why bother with the stealth?

I got a personal message from the producer to test the game on the release date. So I did, and First Stike took me right into full action. I spent at least 90 minutes for the first mission (maybe my tactics were wrong, but this is a different story) and was constantly building, attacking and defending.  The game engine is great: extremely smooth and easy to use interface with lot's of very nice details. It was never so easy to bomb an other country into the stoneage. You learn the controls quick and easy and after some minutes you even skip the tutorials, as the controls are obvious and you just want to conquer the world. The game AI seems to be pretty good, and I guess it will be a lot harder when you try to conquer the earth as North Korea... That said, I would like to say that First Strike is a great game - but you need to calculate some time in, as you can not save the games, but you can pause it.
